<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06193211 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06193211 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  EMPLOYMENT; HOLIDAY; INCREASE; STATE; ELECTION; LEGISLATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Remember all those times, you've muttered, &quot;If I only had more free time, Icould . . .&quot; Well, imagine what you could do with six weeks off from workevery year.;    That's what Richard Such wants people to consider now that thePalo Alto resident and San Francisco attorney received the go-ahead Wednesdayto collect signatures to put a constitutional amendment on the June 1992ballot to guarantee just that.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  P.A. MAN TAKES INITIATIVE TOWARD SIX-WEEKVACATIONS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Fed up with the piddling vacation time employees in the United States get,Such wants to give six weeks of vacation yearly to hard-working, upstandingemployees.;    That proposal was certified on Wednesday by Secretary of StateMarch Fong Eu. Now, Such can begin collecting the 615,958 signatures ofregistered voters needed by Dec. 6 to get the proposal on the Californiaballot.;    &quot;America is archaic in this respect,&quot; Such, 49, said. &quot;The Germanshave a minimum of six weeks' vacation. It hasn't hurt them.&quot;;    Governmentemployees would be exempt to keep the law from costing the state money. Toqualify, workers must be with the same employer for two years and must meetfive of these criteria:;    (check) Have a high school diploma.;    (check)Have voted in the most recent election.;    (check) Take no more than 80 hoursof sick leave a year.;    (check) Not smoke on the job.;    (check) Have nodrunken driving or drug convictions in 10 years.;    (check) Take masstransit, use car pools or walk to work 80 percent of the time.;    Suchbelieves the extra time off will improve worker productivity and cut down onalcohol and drug problems on the job.;    Such, who has three weeks ofvacation, already knows what he'd do with the extra time: &quot;I'd finally cleanout the garage, for sure.&quot;;    IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; You can write to RichardSuch at 2150 Oberlin St., Palo Alto, 94306.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  CAROLYN JUNG, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910711  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  310  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday July 11, 199100193211,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>